.pl 62
                            Chapter 6

                           PROCEDURES

6.1  INTRODUCTION

A  DSI-32  Assembler  procedure is a set of  statements  that  is 
bounded  by a PROC and ENDPROC pseudo-op.  The statements between 
the two pseudo-ops are executed when the procedure is invoked  by 
a  call  procedure  instruction.   Control  is  returned  to  the 
statement  after  the  calling statement on  termination  of  the 
procedure.  A procedure invocation has the following format:

     Block               Description
     -----	         -----------
     Call Block          any parameters required by the procedure 
                         are pushed onto the current  stack.  The 
                         procedure is then called.

     Parameter Block     allocates  storage  for  the  parameters 
                         which  have  been pushed onto the  stack 
                         from the Call Block.
		
     Return Value Block	 allocates  storage  for  any  parameters 
                         which  are  to  be  returned  from   the 
                         procedure.

     Local Variable Block
                         allocates   storage  on  the  stack  for 
                         temporary  data  which is local  to  the 
                         procedure. Any General-Purpose registers 
                         which   need   to  be  saved  prior   to 
                         executing   the  Procedure   Instruction 
                         Block may be saved.

     Procedure Instruction Block
                       the instructions which form the procedure.

The  following procedure management pseudo-ops are  supported  by 
the Assembler:

Pseudo-op             Description		          Section
-----------------------------------------------------------------
PROC	    specifies the start of a procedure block	     6.2
PROCF       specifies the start of a global procedure block  6.2
RETURNS     specifies the start of the return value block    6.3
VAR         specifies the General-Purpose registers to       6.4
	    save and the start of the local variable block
BEGIN       specifies the start of the procedure             6.5
	    instruction block
ENDPROC     terminates the procedure definition              6.6
6.1.1  Procedure Operation

A detailed description of invocation and execution of a procedure 
is shown below:

   - Parameters  required  by the procedure are pushed  onto  the 
     stack by the calling routine.  The parameters are stored  in 
     the Parameter Block.

   - The   calling  routine  executes  the  appropriate   NS32000 
     instruction which either pushes a 32-bit return address onto 
     the  stack,  or if the calling routine is in another module, 
     pushes  a  16-bit  module descriptor address  and  a  32-bit 
     return  address onto the stack.   The procedure then  begins 
     execution.

   - The  procedure  executes  an  ENTER  instruction  (which  is 
     implicitly  generated via the invocation of the VAR  pseudo-
     op).  The  ENTER instruction allocates any required  storage 
     for  temporary  data and then saves the  specified  General-
     Purpose registers onto the stack.

   - The  procedure executes the instructions in the  Instruction 
     Block.

   - The  General-Purpose registers are restored off  the  stack, 
     and  then  control  returns to the  calling  routine's  next 
     instruction.

.pa
6.1.2  Procedure Types

Two types of procedures are implemented:

   - Local Procedures (or Subroutines)

   - External Procedures

Procedures   which  have  local  scope  are  assigned  the  Local 
Procedure  type.  They  may be called from  anywhere  within  the 
module in which they are defined.

Procedures  which  have  public scope are assigned  the  External 
Procedure type.   They may be called from any module in which the 
procedure's  name has been defined with an IMPORTP  directive  or 
colon minus (:-) as well as from within the module in which it is 
defined. When an External Procedure is invoked the current module 
is exited and the new module in which the procedure is defined in 
entered.  Control returns to the calling procedure on termination 
of the External Procedure.


NOTE:     A  recursive procedure is a procedure which contains  a 
          call  block to itself.  Since all parameter storage  is 
          allocated  on  the  stack  and  each  invocation  of  a 
          procedure  automatically reserves  storage,  procedures 
          may  recursively  call themselves as long as  there  is 
          sufficient stack space available. A recursive procedure 
          may  be  either  a  Local  or  External  Procedure.  (A 
          recursive  External  Procedure must be  defined  either 
          with a colon minus (:-) or must be specified in both an 
          IMPORTP and EXPORTP operand list.)
.pa
6.1.3  Procedure Format

A procedure has the following form:

	<label>		PROC
	[<label>]	BLKx
			 .		Parameter Block
                         .
			BLKx
			[RETURNS]
	[<label>]	BLKx
			 .		Return Value Block
                         .
			BLKx
			VAR [reglist]
	[<label>]	BLKx
			 .		Local Variable Block
                         .
			BLKx
			BEGIN
			statement-1
			 .		Procedure Instruc. Block
                         .
			statement-n
			ENDPROC

The  PROC pseudo-op defines the start of a procedure.  The  label 
which  becomes  the procedure name may be a local label (:) or  a 
public label specified by (::) or (:-). A public procedure may be 
called  by  any module in the program in  which  the  procedure's 
label  has  been  imported by an IMPORTP pseudo-op  or  from  the 
module it is defined in.

The  Parameter  Block  is  optional.   If  a  procedure  requires 
parameters,   storage   for   them  must  be  reserved   by   the 
appropriately labeled storage allocation pseudo-ops, in the order 
in which the call block pushes them onto the stack.

The  Return Value Block is optional.  If a procedure has a Return 
Value Block, it may be no larger than the space allocated for the 
parameters since the same storage area is used by both blocks.

The  Local  Variable  Block  is  optional.   The  VAR  pseudo-op, 
however, must be specified. The register list to save and restore 
is optional.
.pa
A  procedure must contain a BEGIN pseudo-op to specify the  start 
of   the  Procedure  Instruction  Block.   An   empty   Procedure 
Instruction  Block  is legal as long as it is terminated  by  the 
ENDPROC  pseudo-op.  The BEGIN pseudo-op causes the assembler  to 
generates  an ENTER instruction which allocates the storage   for 
the  run-time  variables and saves the General-Purpose  registers 
specified by the VAR pseudo-op.  The ENDPROC pseudo-op causes the 
assembler  to generate an EXIT instruction which deallocates  the 
local  variable storage and restores the registers saved  by  the 
ENTER  pseudo-op.  A RET or RXP instruction depending on  whether 
the procedure is local or external, is also generated.

The   procedure  management  pseudo-ops  and  the  various  block 
structures  are described in Sections 6.2 through 6.7.  A  sample 
procedure is described in Section 6.8.

To  assist  the  programmer in visualising  the  structure  of  a 
procedure below is an exploded view of a procedure.

                     ADDP:: PROC
00000009 FP          X:     BLKB    1
00000008 FP          Y:     BLKB    1
                            RETURNS
00000009 FP          Z:     BLKB    1
                            VAR     [R0,R1] ;PRESERVE REGISTERS
FFFFFFFF FP          A:     BLKB   1
00000000 PC 820301          BEGIN
00000003 PC 14C009          MOVB    X,R0    ;GET FIRST VARIABLE
00000006 PC 54C008          MOVB    Y,R1    ;AND SECOND VARIABLE
00000009 PC 4000            ADDB    R0,R1   ;ADD THEM
0000000B PC 140E09          MOVB    R1,Z    ;STORE THE RESULT
0000000E PC 14C6097F        MOVB    Z,A     ;JUST FOR EXAMPLE
00000012 PC 92C01201        ENDPROC

From the above example it can easily be seen that the X, Y, and Z 
variables are not PC relocation but are FP relocation type.  This 
means  that  a routine that wants to call the ADDP  routine  must 
pass the X and Y variables on the stack prior to calling ADDP and 
obtain  the result Y off stack on return from ADDP.  Below is  an 
example of a fragment of code that would be used to call ADDP:

     MOVB      10,TOS         ;PASS THE X VARIABLE FIRST
     MOVB      20,TOS         ;AND THE Y VARIABLE SECOND
     CXP       ADDP           ;CALL THE ADDP PROCEDURE
     MOVB      TOS,R0         ;THE RESULT
.pa
Also  from  the example it can be seen that the  BEGIN  pseudo-op 
causes the ENTER intruction to be generated.  In fact the  actual 
instruction that is generated is:

     ENTER     [R0,R1],1

The  intruction causes 1 byte of local stack space to be reserved 
for the A variable.  The variable A is a local variable that only 
is active while the ADDP procedure is active. Local variables are 
very  useful  in recursive procedures and  whenever  a  temporary 
memory variable is required.

The  ENDPROC  instruction  causes  the assembler  to  output  two 
instructions:

     EXIT      [R0,R1]        ;restore the original R0 and R1
     RXP        1             ;remove only 1 byte of stack 

Note that only one byte of stack is removed,  this is because the 
calling routine removes the final byte of stack.
.pa
6.2  PROC and PROCF Pseudo-op      (PROCF enhanced assembler)

Format:   <label>   PROC | PROCF

description:
          <label>        is the required label.   It defines  the 
                         procedure's  name.   The  scope  of  the 
                         procedure  is  defined as local  (:)  or 
                         public (::, :-) unless PROCF is used.

          PROC | PROCF   is the pseudo-op.

The PROC pseudo-op defines the start of a procedure and the start 
of  the Parameter Block.  The Parameter Block defines the storage 
required  for the parameters to be passed to the  procedure  from 
the calling routine.  The pseudo-op enters the FP relocation mode 
and sets the location counter to 00000000.

The PROCF (Far procedure access) pseudo-op performs all the  same 
functions  as the PROC pseudo-op except that it offers a  special 
feature.  It enables the procedure to be defined as if it was  to 
be  called  via  a CXP instruction without having to  export  the 
procedure label. 

This feature enables a jump table to be constructed such that its 
labels are exported. An example of this feature is shown below:
.uj 0

     CHARIN::    BR   _CHARIN
     CHAROUT::   BR   _CHAROUT
     PRNTOUT::   BR   _PRNTOUT
               .
               .
              etc

     _CHARIN:    PROC           equivalent to  CHARIN::  PROC
               .
               .                except that the label _CHARIN
                 ENDPROC        doesn't have to be exported.

     _CHAROUT:   PROC
               .
               .
                 ENDPROC
.uj 1
.pa
If  parameters  are  to  be  passed  to  the  procedure,  storage 
allocation  pseudo-ops must follow the PROC pseudo-op,  and  they 
must  allocate  the appropriate number of bytes per parameter  in 
the same sequence as the parameters are to be passed.

The  symbols defined in the Parameter Block are assigned FP  type 
and they must be local symbols i.e.,  a single colon must  follow 
the symbol name and it must not be imported or exported.

Example:
          MASSUB::  PROC
          WIDTH:    BLKW      1
          HEIGHT:   BLKW      1
          DEPTH:    BLKW      1

In  the example,  PROC specifies the start of a public  procedure 
which  is assigned the name MASSUB.  The Parameter Block  defines 
storage for three parameters:  WIDTH, HEIGHT, DEPTH. Since MASSUB 
is  a public procedure the initial offset is 12 (0C hex) and  the 
relocation type is FP.

Symbol values and type:

          WIDTH     00000010  FP
          HEIGHT    0000000E  FP
          DEPTH     0000000C  FP

NOTE:  Since the FP addressing mode is relative to the stack, the 
symbols are assigned increasing addresses last symbol first. Thus 
the last symbol,  DEPTH, is assigned the lowest available address 
(FP  0000000C),  while the second to last symbol is assigned  the 
next  lowest  available address.  The allocation of addresses  to 
symbols continues until all the parameters are processed.
.pa
6.3  RETURNS Pseudo-op

Format:   RETURNS

description:
          RETURNS        is the pseudo-op.

The  RETURNS  pseudo-op specifies the start of the  Return  Value 
Block.  The  Return Value Block defines the storage required  for 
the parameters to be returned to the calling routine. The pseudo-
op  enters  the  the  FP relocation mode and  sets  the  location 
counter to 00000000. Since the Return Value Block shares the same 
storage  as the Parameter Block,  the assembler ensures that  the 
Return Value Block is no larger than the Parameter Block.

If  parameters  are to be returned to the  calling  routine,  the 
RETURNS  pseudo-op  must be followed by the  appropriate  storage 
allocation  pseudo-ops.  The symbols defined in the Return  Value 
Block  are assigned FP type.  The symbols must be local  symbols. 
I.e.,  a  single colon must follow the symbol names and they must 
not be imported or exported.

NOTE:     Since the Return Value Block shares the same storage as 
          the Parameter Block, writing to one of the Return Value 
          Block  parameters  will  over-write  the  corresponding 
          passed   parameter  for  the  duration  of  the  called 
          procedure.

Example:

		RETURNS
	MASS:	BLKD	1
	WEIGHT:	BLKD	1

In the example,  RETURNS specifies the start of the Return  Value 
Block. The Return Value Block defines storage for two parameters: 
MASS  and  WEIGHT.  Since the procedure is  public,  the  initial 
location counter is 0000000C FP.

Symbol values and type:

	MASS	0000000C  FP
	WEIGHT	00000010  FP

The  Return Value Block assigns addresses to symbols in the  same 
way  as the Parameter Block does,  i.e.,  the last symbol in  the 
block  is  assigned the lowest available address  and  the  first 
parameter  the  highest  used address.   This method  of  address 
allocation  is  compatible with the order in  which  the  calling 
routine pops the return parameters off the stack.
.pa
6.4  VAR Pseudo-op

Format:   VAR [ <reglist> ]

description:
          VAR            is the pseudo-op.

          <reglist>      is  the optional list of General-Purpose 
                         registers  which are to be saved in  the 
                         stack.  The <reglist> field may  contain 
                         one  or  more register names as long  as 
                         they  are  separated  by   commas.   The 
                         <reglist>  field  must  be  enclosed  in 
                         brackets "[ ]".  The registers may be R0 
                         through  R7 or a symbol which  has  been 
                         assigned  the register type (see Section 
                         2.6.3).

The VAR pseudo-op specifies the start of the Local Variable Block 
and  defines  which of the General-Purpose registers are  to   be 
saved.  The VAR pseudo-op  enters the FP relocation mode and sets 
the location counter to FFFFFFFF.

If  local parameters are required,  the VAR pseudo-op  should  be 
followed by the appropriate storage allocation pseudo-ops.  Prior 
to allocating an address to a symbol in the Local Variable Block, 
the  location counter is decremented by the appropriate number of 
bytes  as specified by the respective storage allocation  pseudo-
op.  The symbols must be local symbols i.e.,  a single colon must 
follow the symbol name and it must not be imported or exported.

Example:

		VAR
	DATA1:	BLKD	1
	DATA2:	BLKD	1
	DATA3:	BLKD	1

In  the example,  VAR specifies the start of the  Local  Variable 
Block.  The  location  counter is set to FFFFFFFF FP.  The  Local 
Variable Block defines storage for three  symbols:  DATA1,  DATA2 
and DATA3. The initial location counter is FFFFFFFF FP.

Symbol values and type:

	DATA1	FFFFFFFFC  FP
	DATA2	FFFFFFFF8  FP
	DATA3	FFFFFFFF4  FP

.pa
6.5  BEGIN Pseudo-op

Format:   BEGIN

description:
          BEGIN          is the pseudo-op.

The   BEGIN  pseudo-op  specifies  the  start  of  the  Procedure 
Instruction  Block  and  sets the location counter  to  the  next 
available PC value.  The pseudo-op causes the assembler to output 
an  ENTER  instruction  which saves any  of  the  General-Purpose 
registers  specified  in  the VAR pseudo-op  and  then  allocates 
storage for the procedure's Local Variables Block (if any).

The   Procedure   Instruction  Block  contains   the   executable 
instructions for the procedure.  The Procedure Instruction  Block 
must end with the ENDPROC pseudo-op (see Section 6.6).

Procedures must not be nested, any attempt to do so will cause an 
error to be reported by the assembler.

Example:

	BEGIN
	MOVXWD	WIDTH,DATA1
	MOVXWD	HEIGHT,DATA2
	MOVXWD	LENGTH,DATA3
	MULD    DATA2,DATA1
	MULD    DATA3,DATA1
	MULD	DENSITY,DATA1
	MOVD	DATA1,DATA2
	MULD	GFORCE,DATA2
	MOVD	DATA1,MASS
	MOVD	DATA2,WEIGHT
	ENDPROC

In  the  example,  BEGIN  specifies the start  of  the  Procedure 
Instruction Block and the ENDPROC pseudo-op terminates it.
.pa
6.6  ENDPROC Pseudo-op

Format:   ENDPROC

description:
          ENDPROC        is the pseudo-op.

The   ENDPROC  pseudo-op  specifies  the  end  of  the  Procedure 
Instruction  Block.    An  EXIT  instruction  is  output  by  the 
assembler which restores the General Purpose registers which were 
specified by the VAR pseudo-op.  Either a return from  subroutine 
(RET)  instruction  or  a Return from  External  Procedure  (RXP) 
instruction is also output depending on whether the procedure was 
local or public.

The location counter is restored to the relocation mode and value 
it had prior to the PROC pseudo-op.

Example:

NULL:	PROC
	VAR
	BEGIN
	ENDPROC

In the example ENDPROC defines the end of the procedure NULL.
.pa
6.7  CALL BLOCK

The  Call  Block  consists of the  instructions  which  move  the 
parameters  required  by  the procedure onto the  stack  and  the 
instruction which invokes the procedure.

The  parameters can be passed by value or by reference either  by 
the use of move instructions or ADDR instructions respectively.

If  the procedure is local,  either a branch or jump  instruction 
may be used to pass control to the procedure. If the procedure is 
public a CXP instruction may be used.

Example:

	MOVW	WIDTH,TOS	;pass WIDTH by value
	MOVW	HEIGHT,TOS	; and HEIGHT
	MOVW	DEPTH,TOS	; and DEPTH last
	CXP	MASSUB		;Invoke the external procedure 
                                 MASS

In  the  example,  the  parameters are passed by  value  by  move 
instructions.   The  procedure may then modify the passed  values 
without  affecting  the  original parameters.  The  procedure  is 
invoked by the CXP instruction since it is an external procedure.
.pa
6.8  SAMPLE PROCEDURE

In  the following example a complete procedure and calling  block 
is  shown.  The procedure has been defined as a public  procedure 
which is thus available to any other module in the program as  an 
external  procedure.  The  Call Block passes three parameters  by 
value via the stack:   WIDTH,  HEIGHT and DEPTH.   Two values are 
returned by the procedure: MASS and WEIGHT.

	Call Block (in current module)

	MOVW	WIDTH,TOS	;pass WIDTH by value
	MOVW	HEIGHT,TOS	; and HEIGHT
	MOVW	DEPTH,TOS	; and DEPTH last
	CXP	MASSUB		;Invoke the external procedure
                                 MASS

	Procedure (in some other module)

MASSUB::	PROC		;The start of the public 
                                 procedure MASSUB
WIDTH:	BLKW	1		;parameter 1
HEIGH:	BLKW	1		;parameter 2
DEPTH:	BLKW	1		;parameter 3

	RETURNS			;define the Return Value Block
MASS:	BLKD	1		;the return mass
WEIGHT:	BLKD	1		;the return weight

	VAR			;define the Local Variable Block
DATA1:	BLKD	1		;local variable 1
DATA2:	BLKD	1		;local variable 2

	BEGIN
	MOVXWD	WIDTH,DATA1	;sign extend parameters
	MOVXWD	HEIGHT,DATA2
	MOVXWD	LENGTH,DATA3
	MULD    DATA2,DATA1	;compute volume
	MULD    DATA3,DATA1
	MULD	DENSITY,DATA1	;mass
	MOVD	DATA1,DATA2
	MULD	GFORCE,DATA2	;weight
	MOVD	DATA1,MASS	;store return parameters
	MOVD	DATA2,WEIGHT
	ENDPROC			;terminate procedure and return
                                 to caller

